x4freetext: Experimental and data processing details
The 3.2 MV PELLETRON accelerator of the
Research Laboratory For Nuclear Reactors at the Tokyo
Institute of Technology.
Lithium target bombarded by 1.5 ns bunch
proton beam. For neutron energies 10-100 keV proton
energy is 1.903 MeV (22 keV above threshold energy of
P-LI7 reaction), pulse repetition rate 2 MHz, average
proton current 5 micro-A. For 550 keV neutron energy
proton energy is 2.3 MeV,pulse repetition rate 4 MHz,
average proton current 9 micro-A (from REL-REF)
.Broad neutron spectrum with maximum at aprx 35 and
550 keV
Anti-Compton Na-I(TL) Spectrometer. Main
detector 15.2 cm diameter and length 30.5 cm was
centered in the hollow NaI(TL)  33.0 cm outer diameter
35.6 cm length Compton-suppression detector - for
gamma detection. Energy resolution is 7% at 0.662 MeV
and time resolution is 4.0 ns for 0.511 MeV gamma
Li-6 glass scintillation detector for neutron
flux monitoring. 5 mm diameter * 5 mm length 6-Li
detector located at 30 cm from neutron source was
used for 10-90 keV region, and 102 mm diameter 6.4
mm length detector located 460 cm from n-source was
used for 550 keV
Flight base is 12 and 20 cm
Pulse height discrimination
Cyclic sample-monitor-blank irradiation
The capture sample was natural La2O3 powder (about
50 g) which was contained in a graphite case with an
inner diameter of 55 mm and an inner length of 14 mm.
A gold (Au) disk with a diameter of 55 mm and a
thickness of 1 mm was used as a standard sample. Each
located at capture sample was an angle of 0 degree with
respect to the proton beam direction. The distance
between the neutron source and the sample was 12 cm for
the measurement in the 10-100 keV region and 20 cm for
that at 550 keV.
total error composed of partial ones given
below
statistical error
Error of the standard cross-section
error of the response function
Error due to the trial function
Resultant error due to weighting function
Error due to the extrapolation of gamma
spectrum
error of sample chemical-impurity
content
error of the multiplicity of observed gamma-rays
The capture cross sections of 139La were derived with
uncertainties of about 5% in the incident neutron
energy region from 10 to 100 keV and at 550 keV.
!Error structure taken from J. of Nucl.Sc. and Techn.,
.Corrections were made for neutron self-shielding and
multiple scattering in the sample, for gamma-ray
absorption and scattering in sample, for neutron
cross-sections employed in calculations
